Witch trials and such are quite interesting once you get beyond the modern stereotype. One thing that's been pointed out is that the clergy had a lot of control over the "trial by God" things they did back then, which is reflected in passing percentages more generous than one would expect from some of them. They very last witch trial in my country was in the 19th century, where a supposed witch requested it for herself. She was an old spinster, and people in the neighborhood were saying she was a witch, so she demanded to be put to the flotation test. Sure enough, she sank, so they pulled her out, and she went home as the smuggest bitch in the land.

This Thread in History
1686 (but actually covers context)

In 1683, for a myriad of reasons, from seeking to preform his holy duty as a Muslim through Jihad, seeking to strike his Von Hapsburg Rivals, and aid the French in the Franco-Dutch War, sultan Mehmed IV would declare war upon the Holy Roman Empire, with the aim to take Vienna.
The Armies of the Holy Roman Empire at this point were veterans of years of war against the French, but consequentially were tied up on the Baltic and French fronts of that war.
The Turks, led by a glory seeking retard decided not to besiege the surrounding fortresses in Hungary and Slovenia and went straight for Vienna. When the mass of roaches, camels, and horses arrived this is what happened
https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=ukyquQkQAYo&t=12s&ab_channel=SandRhomanHistory

If you don't have time to watch 40 minutes of animated early modern warfare, lemme give you the long and the short.

The Turks besieged Vienna, and just before they were able to break the last militia line holding the main wall the Poles made their entrance into the war, with 15,000 Winged Hussars turning the legions of roaches into a field of kebabs

Needless to say the Roaches got stomped on.
The newly founded Holy League would from 1683-1686 focus on taking all Hungarian Lands north of the Danube River, but in 1686, the path to Buda (modern Budapest) was open following years with no major battles on the Balkan Front, the Venetians seized Morea but that's about it.
The battle of Buda was a decisive blow against the Turks, not for the military losses but the giving of Carte Blanche to the cossacks and Germans to kill any muslim or jew leading to a total depopulation of said groups in Hungary.

However, come the December of 1686, a new member had joined the Holy League, the Tsardom of Russia, lead by the newly crowned Peter the Great, leading an army of some 140,000 Russian and Cossack soldiers towards the Port of Azov in the Crimean Khanate.
